# Engineering Standards: Clean, Modular, Fast

## Clean Code
- Prefer simple, readable implementations over clever shortcuts.
- Keep functions focused (single responsibility) and small enough to scan quickly.
- Use explicit, domain-oriented naming for files, symbols, and variables.
- Remove dead code and avoid TODO drift: either implement, ticket, or delete.
- Add concise comments only for non-obvious decisions and trade-offs.

## Modular & Reusable Architecture
- Design features as composable modules with clear boundaries and public APIs.
- Separate concerns (UI, domain, data/infrastructure) to reduce coupling.
- Extract reusable logic into shared components/services/utils only after a real second use.
- Depend on interfaces/contracts, not concrete implementations, when feasible.
- Keep modules testable in isolation and avoid hidden side effects.

## Performance-First Delivery
- Prioritize algorithmic efficiency and avoid unnecessary work in hot paths.
- Measure before and after significant optimizations; avoid blind micro-optimizations.
- Reduce allocations, rerenders, I/O calls, and repeated computations.
- Favor lazy loading, caching, batching, and pagination when appropriate.
- Treat performance regressions as bugs: identify root cause and fix with evidence.
